Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Table 1 'Static extraction method' (Page 2) describes coating intact plant tissue with MIL/IL, incubating, collecting hydrophobic liquid, and adding DNA-enriched MIL/IL directly to qPCR buffer; Abstract (Page 1) and Results (Page 2) state DNA-enriched MIL/IL integrated into qPCR buffer without inhibiting reaction.

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Table 1 'Dispersive extraction method' (Page 2) describes suspending cut-up tissue in Tris-based buffer, adding MIL, vortexing, recovering MIL with a magnet, and pipetting MIL into qPCR buffer; text notes MILs can be rapidly recovered with a magnet (Page 4) and DNA-enriched MIL integrated into qPCR (Pages 2,5).

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Table 1 'One-pot PCR method' (Page 2) describes grinding plant tissue and adding tissue + MIL/IL + qPCR buffer directly to reaction; 'One-pot plant cell lysis and qPCR assay' section (Page 6) describes direct integration into qPCR assay during thermocycling and reports successful qPCR amplification after assay optimization.

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: During optimization of DNA desorption from MIL into a Tris-based buffer, a non-ionic surfactant was added: 'The addition of 0.05% Tween20 to the desorption solution improved DNA recovery...' (Page 4). (This is described as desorption/transfer from MIL, not primary lysis.)

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: ['Fig. 10 (p.10/14): schematic shows static/dispersive one-step lysis & DNA extraction using IL/MIL; desorb directly into qPCR buffer or Tris buffer; no wash/centrifugation steps depicted.', 'p.9/14 Discussion: DNA recovery by desorption into Tris buffer at 90°C or directly into qPCR assay; notes compatibility with downstream methods including sequencing or Qubit detection (explicitly mentioned).', 'p.11/14 Conclusions/Results text: amplification efficiency reported for tissue coated with MIL and reacted in qPCR assay; fluorescence readout compatible; indicates one-pot qPCR assay is reliable with MIL.', 'p.12/14 qPCR assays and conditions: qPCR reactions contained 0.05% Tween20 (detergent) in the one-pot qPCR assay mixture; thermocycling includes temperatures >40°C; thus not heat-free.']

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Page 13/14, section 'Plant cell lysis conditions using MILs and ILs': describes a static one-step lysis/DNA extraction by coating intact plant tissue with MIL/IL and incubating at 25 °C; DNA-enriched MIL added to qPCR assay and 'successfully integrated into the qPCR buffer without inhibiting the reaction'. No wash or centrifugation mentioned for the static method.

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Page 13/14, section 'Plant cell lysis conditions using MILs and ILs': dispersive one-step lysis/extraction includes recovery of MIL with a rod magnet and 'washed once with water'; DNA desorption either during qPCR thermocycling or by heating; no centrifugation mentioned; qPCR compatibility stated.

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Page 13/14, paragraph 'Conventional plant cell lysis was performed using the CTAB lysis and extraction method...': CTAB lysis buffer used; centrifugation explicitly mentioned for phase separation and pelleting; heat at 60 °C stated; DNA 'reconstituted ... for downstream bioanalytical detection' (assay not specified). No wash step explicitly described.

Paper_title: Simple and efficient isolation of plant genomic DNA using magnetic ionic liquids
Provenance: Page 13/14, same 'Conventional plant cell lysis...' paragraph: 'SDS lysis was performed' (referencing Marengo et al.); heating at 100 °C stated; centrifugation stated ('sample was centrifuged...'); downstream compatibility not explicitly stated here.
